search.slidetext: why okrs? okrs stand for objectives and key results. it is a collaborative method used by organizations & teams to focus efforts on the same important goals. vocabulary matters! when everyone on the team has a common vocabulary for what matters, it helps teams make better decisions. okrs are a valuable tool in your vocabulary for leadership. this common language for success helps communicate values, priorities, and goals. okrs link goals to the teams broader mission. they steer us to goals that expand limitations and move us towards goals. these goals are pivitol to the formation and execution of okrs. goals are what you want to accomplish. they are what you want to do. if the goal is the destination, the journey is the steps needed to accomplish said goal. so begin with the end in mind! where should you be at the end of your journey? by using okrs we will build a roadmap to these goals. okrs link goals!

to help illustrate this journey, we will follow madelines creamery as they create their own okrs for their brand-new fleet of ice cream trucks. lets follow the ice cream truck as their team makes their own okrs, while doing so, think of your own goals. consider how they may expand, exemplify or even challenge the paradigms exemplified by madelines creamery and their fleet of ice cream trucks. in this module, youll be asked to share these goals, reflect on them, and submit them for feedback. lets get started!

objectives! o is for objectives! objectives are ambitious but realistic goals that need to be completed by the end of a cycle. objectives may be described as a destination for yourself and your team. they are clearly defined and measurable. utilize inspiring language and encourage your team to be ambitious but realistic! madelines creamery has written the following objective: objective: increase profits 50% by the end of the year.

types of objectives there are many different types of objectives.! lets take a look at the them now! this objective is focused on your internal team of employees, one of your most valuable assets. this objective may include goals related to hiring, retention, employee engagement, or fostering company culture. people focused objective aspirational roof shot objectives the success of this goal is ambitious and may seem lofty, but they still exist within the teams trajectory and capacity. business maintenance priority objective. this success of this objective is critical to the success of the team or business. committed action objective a specific goal or target that an individual or team actively commits to achieving within a defined timeframe.

objectives! madelines creamery! madelines creamery would like to increase profits 50% by selling more product! they have written the following business maintainence objective: to track the journeys progress, the ice cream truck has identified key milestones. these milestones are called key results. lets take a closer look! to justify the addition of the ice cream trucks and recoup costs, the ice cream trucks will increase the profits of madelines creamery by 50%

lets practice! but first, lets practice writing own objective! write a committed action and/or business maintenance priority. write your answer in the space below: write your objective below: business maintenance priority objective: this success of this objective is critical to the success of the team or business committed action objective: a specific goal or target that an individual or team actively commits to achieving within a defined timeframe. i am writing a _____ objective: business maintenance priority committed action objective both other business maintenance priority objective business maintenance priority objective business maintenance priority objective business maintenance priority objective business maintenance priority objective business maintenance priority objective committed action objective committed action objective committed action objective committed action objective committed action objective committed action objective both both both both both both other other other other other other

goals should have a deadline. without a deadline, success nor failure can be identified. this does not mean that all the work is done, but it does mean that you can evaluate the success of the endeavor and set new goals. timed s.m.a.r.t achievable goals need to be realistic to maintain enthusiasm to try to achieve them. s.m.a.r.t relevant goals should be aligned with the mission of the company. to determine if the goal is relevant is to define the key benefit to the organization. s.m.a.r.t specific define what will be accomplished and the actions to be taken to accomplish the goal. specific goals have a desired outcome that is clearly understood. the goal should be clearly articulated so that everyone is on the same page with the objective. s.m.a.r.t s.m.a.r.t measurable define what data will be used to measure the goal and set a method for collection. these are the numbers used with the goal. quantifiable objectives are needed to track progress. smart s.m.a.r.t s.m.a.r.t another important tip when writing objectives is to make sure that they are s.m.a.r.t. click each letter of the acronym below to learn its meaning and definition. once finished, click next to continue

review the trucks aspirational objective: the ice cream truck must sell more product. their objective is to increase monthly sales by 20% by the end of q3 through the geographical expansion for sales locations. take a moment to review your objective! does it meet the smart criteria? review your objective below. edit until it reflects each s.m.a.r.t. criteria. on finished, flip the switch to confirm.

key results! krs are for key results! key results are the measurements/results we need to achieve our objectives. if an objective is a destination that you set out for your team, key results are your milestone markers. they let you know whether you are getting closer to the destination. they may also let you know when youve taken a wrong turn or are off track. krs are how your measure success! key results need to be quantifiable and measurable. it is not a key result without a number. you should have 3-5 key results per objective madelines creamerys key results to achieve their objective is to sell 1,250 cones per quarter: objective: the ice cream trucks will increase the profits of madelines creamery by 50.

types of objectives level one text level two text level three text level four text level five text key takeaway outcome based key results like objectives, there are many types of key results, in this module, we will focus on outcome based key results. people focused objective outcome: this is focused on financial performance, capital growth and profitability. this often fuels growth in other areas. aspirational roof shot objectives the success of this goal is ambitious and may seem lofty, but they still exist within the teams trajectory and capacity. business maintenance priority objective. this success of this objective is critical to the success of the team or business. business maintenance key result are the measurements/results we need to achieve our objectives. what is an outcome? an outcome may be defined as, what has changed as a result of your work. they define the impact of your actions. when a team focuses on impact rather than mere tasks, it gives people more space to find new and innovative solutions to reach their goals. ask yourself what measure truly means you are making progress and remember, the best key result challenge teams. they do not maintain the status quo. what is not an outcome: as mentioned previously, outcomes are not a list of tasks. outcome based key results should not be a checklist of everything the business is doing and every task that needs to be accomplished. instead, they should be strives to be meaningful, impactful goals that seek innovation, collaboration, and creativity. that isnt to say day-to-day work isnt an important part of your okrs! quite the opposite! it is important to delineate the daytoday work that is necessary to keep the lights. but they have their own place in the okr writing process! the key tasks and activities that support key results are called key initiatives! remember! key results should not be a checklist of tasks. tasks are best reserved for key initiatives.

key initiatives! ki is for key initiative! key initiatives are the projects and activities which will help achieve outcomes. they are the core activities that will drive success of the outcomes defined in your key results. kis must be: timebound, focused, trackable, & clear. madelines creamery has written the following key results to achieve their objective: ki 1: expand geographical area by 25% ki 2: add 5 additional stops to each ice cream trucks route ki 3: add 4 new flavors, 1 per quarter, to the menu
